	"conclusion": "For OpenAI, the career page partially precedes Glassdoor: 28% of matched jobs (24/87) appeared on the career page first, with an average lead of 118 days (median: 75 days). An additional 520 jobs (86% of career-page listings) were never indexed by Glassdoor at all. This confirms that the career page is the primary source of truth for job postings.",
	"geminiSummary": "An analysis of job postings from January 1, 2024, to April 1, 2026, reveals a distinct advantage for company career pages in publishing job opportunities ahead of Glassdoor. Among 87 job postings matched across both platforms, career pages posted first for 24 roles (28%), while Glassdoor posted first for 61, and two appeared on the same day. For those 24 instances where career pages led, the average publishing lag before Glassdoor was a substantial 118 days, with a median lag of 75 days. This significant lead is exemplified by \"Software Engineer, Data Infrastructure,\" which appeared on a career page 476 days earlier (June 27, 2024 vs. October 16, 2025), and \"Software Engineer, Real Time,\" which was listed 463 days ahead (July 10, 2024 vs. October 16, 2025).\n\nThe distribution of these lags offers critical insights for job seekers. While a significant portion of jobs (9 out of 24) appeared on career pages 90 or more days before Glassdoor, providing an extremely long window, a meaningful number of opportunities also became available with shorter, yet still crucial, leads. Three jobs were posted 1–3 days earlier, and another three appeared 8–14 days ahead. Additionally, one job was listed 15–30 days prior, three between 31–60 days, and five between 61–90 days. This pattern indicates that while some roles benefit from extensive early visibility, a noticeable segment of positions offers a competitive advantage to direct career page monitors within a matter of days or a few weeks before broader aggregation.\n\nIt is important to interpret these findings with several caveats in mind. The analysis period spanned over two years, yet only 6 Glassdoor snapshots were processed compared to 200 career page snapshots. This significant disparity in monitoring frequency for Glassdoor could potentially skew the observed lag times and Glassdoor's perceived \"first\" count. Furthermore, out of 607 unique jobs found on career pages, only 120 were identified on Glassdoor, with just 87 successfully matched across both platforms, suggesting potential limitations in Glassdoor's crawl coverage or matching capabilities for this dataset. The 520 jobs identified exclusively on career pages further highlight that many opportunities may simply not be aggregated by Glassdoor at all.\n\nGiven these insights, job seekers aiming for a competitive edge should prioritize directly monitoring company career pages. This strategy provides early access to a substantial number of positions, offering a lead that can range from a few days to several months. Specifically, candidates could potentially see jobs 1–14 days before they appear on Glassdoor for at least six matched roles in this study, providing a crucial head start in the application and preparation process. Relying solely on aggregators like Glassdoor risks missing out on a significant portion of available jobs (520 in this dataset never reached Glassdoor) and diminishes the chance of being among the first applicants for roles that do eventually appear on both platforms.",
	"geminiAvailable": true
}